  number={},
  pages={1-6},
  abstract={Early detection of mental health disorders through social media has become a crucial focus in the advancement of machine learning-based technologies. This study presents a systematic review of 40 research papers investigating various mental conditions such as depression, anxiety, stress, PTSD, suicidal ideation, and eating disorders. The data utilized includes social media texts (Twitter, Reddit), EEG signals, and multimodal input from passive sensing devices. Diverse approaches were employed, ranging from classical models like Logistic Regression and Naive Bayes to transformer-based models such as BERT and RoBERTa, as well as hybrid architectures (CNN-BiLSTM, Attention Layer). Several studies have shown very high performance, with one of them achieving up to 99% accuracy in classifying depression. However, challenges remain, including data annotation quality, class imbalance, and limited crossdomain and population validation. This review emphasizes the importance of adaptive and context-aware approaches for accurately and reliably detecting various mental conditions in real-world scenarios.},
  keywords={Performance evaluation;Machine learning algorithms;Social networking (online);Mental health;Depression;Brain modeling;Transformers;Sensors;Reliability;Systematic literature review;Mental Health;Social Media;Machine Learning;Naturak Language Processing;Early Detection},
