  year={2024},
  volume={1},
  number={},
  pages={1-6},
  abstract={Depression is a serious mental illness which impacts an excessive amount of people all over the world. The assessment, treatment, and prevention of depressive symptoms necessitate the timely identification of such symptoms. As datasets pertaining to depression continue to grow and machine learning techniques advance, there is potential for the development of intelligent methods to detect depression in written content. Millions of people all around the world suffer from the mental illness anxiety. The assessment, treatment, and prevention of depression recurrence necessitate the timely identification of depressive symptoms. As the availability of depression-related datasets increases and machine learning techniques advance, there is potential for the development of intelligent methods to detect depression in written material. This research paper presents ainnovative approach for predicting depression from text by utilizing the Bi-directional Long-Short Term Memory (Bi-LSTM) model. The proposed model aims to contribute to the prevention of mental disorders and suicidal tendencies by effectively identifying individuals at risk. In this study, a Bi-LSTM model is employed to train on textual data in order to detect signs of depression. The focus of the research is to analyze the text's semantics and written content to accurately identify instances of depression. The proposed framework demonstrates a notable achievement of 99.8% accuracy, surpassing frequency-based deep learning models. Additionally, the framework successfully mitigates the false positive rate. In addition to evaluating the proposed model, authors conduct a comparative analysis with other existing models in terms of their mean accuracy. The feasibility of Bi-LSTM is demonstrated by the proposed approach, which achieves exceptional results in the recognizing signs of sadness in the online comments of a large number of users.},
